From: Amaan Qureshi <amaanq@nixos.org>
Subject: [PATCH] bcachefs: surface bch_folio UAF candidates with WARN_ONCE

Diagnostic patch carried in bunker. A reclaim-path crash was hit on a
buffered-I/O workload:

  BUG: unable to handle page fault for address: ffff8c4dff8118e0
  RIP: 0010:_raw_spin_lock+0x17/0x40
  Call Trace:
   bch2_set_folio_undirty+0x40/0x180 [bcachefs]
   bch2_release_folio+0x68/0xc0 [bcachefs]
   shrink_folio_list+0xdea/0x1800
   evict_folios+0x15f5/0x1ed0
   ...
   kswapd+0xdd0/0x18e0

The fault address has no direct-map backing (PUD entry zero), which is
consistent with KFENCE having torn down the page after a kfree() of the
bch_folio. To find the caller hitting bch2_folio() with either:

  (a) folio->private holding a stale/garbage value while PG_private is
      clear — the field aliases folio->swap in the kernel struct, so a
      raw read can return either a dangling pointer or a swap-entry bit
      pattern, or

  (b) bch2_set_folio_undirty() being entered without the folio lock,
      which is the contract its only caller (bch2_clear_folio_bits)
      relies on before calling __bch2_folio_release()→kfree(),

instrument the two spots once and dump the call stack on first hit. The
WARN_ONCE keeps log volume bounded; the stack trace identifies which
caller is violating the invariant. Once we've localized that, the real
fix replaces this patch.

Carried in bunker only — do not upstream.
---
 fs/vfs/pagecache.c | 14 +++++++++++++-
 fs/vfs/pagecache.h | 17 ++++++++++++++++-
 2 files changed, 29 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

--- a/fs/vfs/pagecache.h
+++ b/fs/vfs/pagecache.h
@@ -101,7 +101,22 @@

 static inline struct bch_folio *bch2_folio(struct folio *folio)
 {
-	return folio_get_private(folio);
+	void *priv = folio_get_private(folio);
+
+	/*
+	 * DIAGNOSTIC (bunker): folio->private is in a union with folio->swap.
+	 * If PG_private isn't set, the field can hold either a stale pointer
+	 * (UAF on a dangling bch_folio) or a swap-entry bit pattern. Either
+	 * way, dereferencing it explodes — flag the caller and return NULL.
+	 */
+	if (unlikely(priv && !folio_test_private(folio))) {
+		WARN_ONCE(1,
+			"bcachefs: bch2_folio: priv=%px on folio %px without PG_private (mapping=%px index=%lu)\n",
+			priv, folio, folio->mapping, folio->index);
+		return NULL;
+	}
+
+	return priv;
 }

 struct bch_folio *__bch2_folio_create(struct folio *, gfp_t);
--- a/fs/vfs/pagecache.c
+++ b/fs/vfs/pagecache.c
@@ -524,7 +524,19 @@
 			    struct folio *folio,
 			    size_t offset, size_t len)
 {
-	struct bch_folio *s = bch2_folio(folio);
+	struct bch_folio *s;
+
+	/*
+	 * DIAGNOSTIC (bunker): this function frees nothing on its own, but
+	 * bch2_clear_folio_bits() (its only caller) goes on to kfree the
+	 * bch_folio via __bch2_folio_release(). The folio MUST be locked
+	 * for that to be safe — surface any caller that violates this.
+	 */
+	WARN_ONCE(!folio_test_locked(folio),
+		"bcachefs: bch2_set_folio_undirty: folio %px not locked (mapping=%px index=%lu)\n",
+		folio, folio->mapping, folio->index);
+
+	s = bch2_folio(folio);
 	if (!s)
 		return;

